<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-513-967  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 513 967.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Sept 26 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>900 number leaves voice mail for the president, congress.andO;(Congressional Voice Mail Service from Tela)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Tela (information services).andO;Topic:     AudiotexVoice MailUnited States. CongressPolitics.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>900 NUMBER LEAVES VOICE MAIL FOR THE PRESIDENT, CONGRESS DENVER, COLORADO,U.S.A., 1990 SEP 26 (NB) -- Audiotex brokerage Tela has bought CongressionalVoice Mail Service, which runs a 900 number that allows Americans send voicemail messages to the President and Congress.andP;  The cost of the call is $2 perminute.andM;Theodore Larson of Tela told Newsbytes: &quot;We're planning to make thisavailable to political action groups.andP;  The main calls we get are people whowant to talk about a bill or tell the President he's doing a good job.andP;  Thereare a few calls from people who want help.andP;  In those cases we try to helpthem out immediately, as well as pass the message along.&quot;andM;The number is 900-740-3030.andP;  Using a touchtone phone, the caller can leavemessages for any Senator or Representative, the President or Vice-President,and without a touchtone phone the caller can automatically leave a messagefor the President.andP;  Senate and Congressional leadership can be reacheddirectly and all others are accessed using a two letter state abbreviation.andM;&quot;We recommend that callers prepare their messages ahead of time in order tosave money and get their point across,&quot; Larson added.andP;  &quot;Callers can also getinformation on the Senate and House agenda for each day so that they cancomment on current legislation, and they can leave a name and address to besent the instructions, further cutting the cost of contacting theirrepresentatives.&quot;andM;Larsen said most political uses of 900 numbers are specific, citing one adagainst the proposed Flag-Burning Amendment, and another number used by theNRA to create mail.andP;  &quot;We can also set up a number for specific causes.andP;  We'llget the number, get the computer, and do the service on it,&quot; he said.andM;Still, &quot;It seems to me, and I have no proof of this, that Congress willlisten closely if they think it's the voice of real Americans.andP;  When they geta 10-foot stack of letters from the NRA, they just measure it.andP;  But we havethings like high school students giving specific suggestions to the Presidentbased on their papers.andP;  That's what we're trying to do.&quot;andM;(Dana Blankenhorn/19900925/Press Contact: Ted Larson, Tela, 303- 893-5150)</TEXT></DOC>